North Korea said that disarmament could in no case be done unilaterally without confidence.
On Saturday, the North Korean Minister for Foreign Affairs stated to the United Nations that the maintenance of sanctions would strengthen his mistrust against the United States and that it would be impossible for his country to unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
At the annual General Assembly of the World Organization, Ri Yong Ho stated that last year North Korea had taken “important measures of goodwill”, such as the cessation of nuclear tests and missiles, the demantling of the nuclear testing site and its commitment to not proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
"But we see no corresponding response from the United States," he regretted.
In the absence of confidence in the United States, we will fear our national security and, in such circumstances, it is excluded that we are the first to disarm ourselves unilaterally."
While repeating the well-known reproachs of North Korea regarding Washington's opposition to a "step-step" approach to denuclearization, which would reward North Korea if it took steps gradually, its statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong One and Donald Trump, held on 12 June in Singapore at the very first summit between a President-in-Office of the United States and a North Korean leader, when Kim committed to promoting "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula" while Trump promised to ensure the security of North Korea.
North Korea seeks to formally end the Korean war (1950-1953), but the United States stated that Pyongyang had to give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington also refused requests to facilitate severe international sanctions against North Korea.
The United States insists that North Korea should first proceed to denuclearization and intensify pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve their goal in a coercive manner, even against "the declaration of the end of war".
"Those who think that these sanctions can make us be imposed do not know us.
The problem is that the maintenance of sanctions increases our mistrust."
Ri did not comment on the second summit between Kim and Trump highlighted by the American leader earlier this week before the United Nations.
Instead, the Minister emphasized three meetings between Kim and the South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, and added: “If the party concerned with the issue of denuclearization was South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such an impasse.”
Despite all this, the tone of Ri's speech was radically different from that of last year, when he stated to the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable to point the North Korean missiles into the North American territory after "malicious" President Trump called Kim "missile man" as a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened the United Nations last year to "completely destroy" North Korea, did not praise this year the courage with which Kim applied disarmament measures, but added that there was still much to do and that sanctions would not be lifted until North Korea was disarmed.
On Wednesday, Trump said that no deadline had been set. "This can take two years, three years or five months; this is of no importance," he said.
China and Russia argue that the United Nations Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures adopted.
