This year, the Harvard University has launched a new course that allows all early-stage students to sleep more and fight the growing machist trend of studying by taking cafetine all night.
One teacher noticed that most students from the world's best university don't know how to take care of them.
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at the Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is, according to him, the first of the kind in the United States.
After giving a conference on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning, the idea came to him
At the end, a student approached me and said, "Why are they telling me this only in the last year?"
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he entrusted The Telegraph.
This course, for the first time this year, explains the need for students to adopt good sleeping habits to improve their school and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Director General of University Health Services, said that the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students were suffering from severe sleep shortages during the week.
The course time consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections shows the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee cups, curtains, baskets, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine before bed.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep loss can increase the risk of heart attack, AVC, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
"We know that this will not immediately change the behaviour of students.
However, in our opinion, they have the right to know this information - in the same way as you have the right to know the effects of smoking on health," said Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride to spend "a white night" still exists, and he adds that modern technology and increasing pressure on students make the lack of sleep a growing problem.
Having sufficient and good quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" of students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid taking weight, because the lack of sleep puts the brain in an inanition mode, making them hungry constantly.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student in chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year in Harvard.
He argued that this course had opened his eyes and urged him to insist that he should be offered to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to propose to all students in the third cycle to follow a similar study program before joining the renowned institution.
