Syria is "prepared" for the return of refugees, according to the Minister for Foreign Affairs
Syria stands ready for the voluntary return of refugees and seeks assistance to rebuild the country devastated by a war that has lasted for more than seven years.
Addressing the United Nations General Assembly, Minister for Foreign Affairs, Walid al-Moualem, said that the situation in the country was improving.
"Today, the situation on site is more stable and safe thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism," he said.
The Government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists in order to restore normality.
All conditions are now met for the voluntary repatriation of refugees in the country they have been forced to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have desertified the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian regime would welcome aid for the reconstruction of this devastated country.
However, he stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or assistance from countries that sponsored the insurrection.
