Point info on the red tide: Lower concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The final report of the Commission on Fisheries and Wildlife in Florida indicates a general decrease in the concentrations of red tide in certain areas of the Tampa Bay region.
According to the PSC, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which is a fear of lower concentrations.
The red tide covers about 209 km (130 miles) of coastlines, from north of Pinellas to south of the counties of Lee.
There are islands about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but in fewer sites than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off the Pinellas county were reported last week, low to high concentrations in the Hillsborough county, higher concentrations in the Manatee county, higher concentrations at the bottom of the Sarasota county or off, average concentrations in the Charlotte county and low concentrations in the Lee county and on the side, high concentrations at the bottom or off the Collier county.
Respiratory irritation persists in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory irritation has been reported in the northwest of Florida over the past week.
